title: For Sale:  DPMS LR-308 (AR 10) .308 WIN Hog Slayer!
postcontent:
I am selling my DPMS LR-308 with the following upgrades:
Tri-Delta Steel Muzzle Brake, Picatinny Rail Handguards, 800 Lumen Flashlight w/mount, Tactical Foregrip w/ bi-pod, Tactical Pistol Grip, Vltor Mod 4 Charging Handle (Large Latch), Quick-Release Sling Swivel, Israeli Sniper Butt Stock w/adjustable cheek rest and Leupold VXR Patrol 3-9x40mm Scope w/ Fire Dot Reticle and Leupold Scope Mounts. I am also including 2 - 30 round steel magazines, 2 boxes of Hornady .308 WIN 155 gr OTM W/C Match-Grade Ammo, 15 rounds of Remington .308 WIN 168 gr Hog Hammer Ammo and a locking hard case (w/ keys). I will also throw in a handful of 147gr FMJ. The rifle does not like them so I only shot a couple out of the box.
The rifle is about 4 months old and has had about 150 rounds put through it and dropped numerous hogs over the Summer. It is broken in but has not been abused. I have fired one magazine rapid-fire just to ensure that the rifle would cycle rounds that quickly if I wished to do so. I bought it to shoot hogs not to play Army so I have not had the need to do so a second time. And good ammo is too expensive to burn through pointlessly. 
The scope is zeroed dead on at 100 yards. The Fire Dot reticle is awesome. Since I zeroed the scope at least 90% of my shots were quick shots that I would not have had time to take aim with a normal scope reticle and would likely not have even been able to see the reticle in the very low-light conditions. I just put that red dot on the pig and it's over. I have dropped pigs from 25 yards to 320 yards with no problem.
My cost to build the rifle to its current state is $2,677. I will sell it without the scope for $1700 or with the scope for $2200.
I would consider offers of trades for a crossbow, higher magnification scope, Taurus Judge Magnum or other handgun of at least .45 ACP caliber, or other hunting gear of good quality plus cash.

title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W 32 Double Action 4th Model
postcontent:
Caliber: .32 S&W, double-action revolver, 5-shot fluted cylinder with a nominal length of .92”. Barrel lengths of 3” or 3-1/2” are common, with 6” somewhat scarce, and 8” or 10” quite rare. Changes are the rounded-rear trigger guard replacing the reverse curved trigger guard. Standard finish is blue or nickel. Stocks are checked black hard rubber with S&W monogram on a round butt frame, pinned round blade front sight, with a notch cut into the barrel latch for a rear sight. Top-break action with auto extraction of spent shells. The sideplate on the frame’s left side is held in place with one screw. Serial number range 43406 - about 282999. Roughly 239,600 were manufactured c. 1883 – 1909.

This particular revolver has a serial number of 236XXX and has the 3.5 inch barrel.  It is in excellent condition for its age except for one grip which has been broken (please see pictures for further detail).  This gun is still able to function with the broken grip and it can be replaced.  The gun fires and locks up tight.  Extractor functions as it should.  Great Piece of history.

Im not sure if its because i havent ever set the bolt to the proper speed, or if it is ware on one of the smaller parts, but if you intend to use this for rapid fire, dont. The bottom of the clip that secures the bayonet has been sanded to bare metal.  All misgivings aside, great rifle, love it. Ive just moved to the AR-15 and have no room. Originally purchased for $650 ( i was an idiot 17 year old with a load of cash to blow... )
